  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Videos: What is the file size per hour of recording 720p of video?",
  "response": "The file size per hour of recording 720p video can vary depending on several factors such as the codec used, the bitrate, and the level of compression. However, here are some general estimates:\n\n- **H.264 Codec**: A common bitrate for 720p video using the H.264 codec is around 3-5 Mbps (Megabits per second). \n\n  To calculate the file size for one hour:\n  - At 3 Mbps: \\( 3 \\text{ Mbps} \\times 3600 \\text{ seconds} = 10,800 \\text{ Megabits} \\)\n  - Convert Megabits to Megabytes: \\( 10,800 \\text{ Mb} \\div 8 = 1,350 \\text{ MB} \\) or approximately 1.35 GB.\n  - At 5 Mbps: \\( 5 \\text{ Mbps} \\times 3600 \\text{ seconds} = 18,000 \\text{ Megabits} \\)\n  - Convert Megabits to Megabytes: \\( 18,000 \\text{ Mb} \\div 8 = 2,250 \\text{ MB} \\) or approximately 2.25 GB.\n\n- **H.265 (HEVC) Codec**: This codec is more efficient and might use a bitrate of around 1.5-3 Mbps for 720p.\n\n  To calculate the file size for one hour:\n  - At 1.5 Mbps: \\( 1.5 \\text{ Mbps} \\times 3600 \\text{ seconds} = 5,400 \\text{ Megabits} \\)\n  - Convert Megabits to Megabytes: \\( 5,400 \\text{ Mb} \\div 8 = 675 \\text{ MB} \\) or approximately 0.68 GB.\n  - At 3 Mbps: \\( 3 \\text{ Mbps} \\times 3600 \\text{ seconds} = 10,800 \\text{ Megabits} \\)\n  - Convert Megabits to Megabytes: \\( 10,800 \\text{ Mb} \\div 8 = 1,350 \\text{ MB} \\) or approximately 1.35 GB.\n\nSo, for 720p video, you can expect the file size to range roughly from 0.68 GB to 2.25 GB per hour, depending on the codec and bitrate settings used.",
